The '''European Organization for Nuclear Research''' ({{lang-fr|Organisation européenne pour la recherche nucléaire}}), <!-- The official name contains organization/organisation NOT council/conseil. Read the history section before you vandalize the article. -->known as '''CERN'''<!-- The acronym is explained in CERN's website: https://home.cern/about --> ({{IPAc-en|s|ɜːr|n}}; {{IPA-fr|sɛʁn}}; derived from the name ''Conseil européen pour la recherche nucléaire''), is a [[Europe]]an research organization that operates the largest [[particle physics]] laboratory in the world. Established in 1954, the organization is based in a northwest suburb of [[Geneva]] on the Franco–Swiss border, ({{coord|46|14|3|N|6|3|19|E}}) and has 22 [[#Member states and budget|member states]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://international-relations.web.cern.ch/International-Relations/ms/ |title=Member States |website=International Relations |publisher=CERN |accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref> [[Israel]] is the only non-European country granted full membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cerncourier.com/cws/article/cern/55869|title=CERN to admit Israel as first new member state since 1999 - CERN Courier|author=|date=|website=cerncourier.com}}</ref> CERN is an official [[United Nations General Assembly observers|United Nations Observer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/sections/member-states/intergovernmental-organizations/index.html|title=Intergovernmental Organizations|author=|date=|website=www.un.org}}</ref>

The acronym CERN is also used to refer to the laboratory, which in 2016 had 2,500 scientific, technical, and administrative staff members, and hosted about 12,000 users. In the same year, CERN generated 49 [[petabyte]]s of data.<ref name="infigures">{{cite web|url=https://cds.cern.ch/record/2270805/files/486-1611-1-SM.pdf |title=Annual Report 2016 |publisher=CERN |accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>

CERN's main function is to provide the [[particle accelerator]]s and other infrastructure needed for high-energy physics research – as a result, numerous experiments have been constructed at CERN through international collaborations. The main site at [[Meyrin]] hosts a large computing facility, which is primarily used to [[computer data storage|store]] and [[data analysis|analyse data]] from experiments, as well as [[simulation|simulate]] [[event (particle physics)|events]]. Researchers need remote access to these facilities, so the lab has historically been a major [[wide area network]] hub. CERN is also the birthplace of the [[World Wide Web]].<ref>{{cite book
